I"T<h2 id="solution">Solution:</h2>

<p>We will use induction. First, we conjecture that
\(\begin{align*}
        \sum_{i = 1}^{n} a_i &amp;= [c_1(1) + c_2] + [c_1(2) + c_2] + \cdots + [c_1(n) + c_2] \\
        &amp;= c_1(1 + 2 + \cdots + n) + nc_2 \\
        &amp;= c_1\left(\frac{n(n + 1)}{2}\right) + \frac{2nc_2}{2} \\
        &amp;= \left(\frac{n}{2}\right)[c_1(n + 1) + 2c_2]
    \end{align*}\)</p>

<p>For the base case, consider $n = 1$. Clearly, 
\(a_1 = \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)(2c_1 + 2c_2) = c_1(1) + c_2\)</p>

<p>For the inductive hypothesis (IH), assume
\(\sum_{i = 1}^{n - 1} a_i = \left(\frac{n - 1}{2}\right)[c_1n + 2c_2]\)
Now, for the inductive step we have
\(\sum_{i = 1}^n a_i = \sum_{i = 1}^{n - 1} a_i + a_n\ \ih\ \left(\frac{n - 1}{2}\right)[c_1n + 2c_2] + [c_1n + c_2] = c_1\left(\frac{n(n + 1)}{2}\right) + nc_2\)</p>

\[\qed\]
